<li id="cite_note-25"><b><a href="#cite_ref-25" title="">^</a></b> "As construed by the Supreme Court in the <i>Brushaber</i> case, the power of Congress to tax income derives from Article I, Section 8, Clause 1, of the original Constitution rather than from the Sixteenth Amendment; the latter simply eliminated the requirement that an income tax, to the extent that it is a direct tax, must be apportioned among the states." <a href="/wiki/Boris_Bittker" title="Boris Bittker">Boris I. Bittker</a>, Martin J. McMahon, Jr. &amp; Lawrence A. Zelenak, <i>Federal Income Taxation of Individuals</i>, ch. 1, paragr. 1.01[1][a], Research Institute of America (2d ed. 2005), as retrieved from 2002 WL 1454829 (W. G. &amp; L.).</li>
